    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-04-16T03:46:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-04-16T03:46:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/4–352: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief, United Nations Command (<persName
                            corresp="#p_RGMB1" type="from">Ridgway</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of the Army</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-04-16T17:46:00+09:00"
                            >April 16, 1952—5:46 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>CX 67005. 1. At the completion of Opn <gloss target="#t_SCATTER1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scatter</hi>
                    </gloss> it will be nec to reclassify those South Korean, North Korean, and
                    Chinese <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POWs</gloss> refusing to return to enemy
                    control. Our present planned procedure is to reclassify and segregate: <list>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                        <item>South Korean <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POWs</gloss> refusing return to
                            enemy control as “civilian internees.”</item>
                        <pb facs="0189" n="155" xml:id="pg_155"/>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                        <item>North Korean and Chinese <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POWs</gloss>
                            refusing return to enemy control as “displaced persons in protective
                            custody of the United Nations Command.”</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>2. <gloss target="#t_CGAE1">CGArEight</gloss> would be instructed to treat
                    “displaced persons in protective custody of United Nations Command” in
                    accordance with the humanitarian principles of the 1949 Geneva Prisoner of War
                    Conventions. The administration of civilian internees would continue to be in
                    accordance with our C 58702, Dec. 51.<note n="1" xml:id="d91fn1">Dated Dec. 5,
                        1951, not printed. (<gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> files)</note>
                </p>
                <p>3. Rosters of individuals reclassified in accordance with procedure outlined in
                    Para 1 would be furnd <gloss target="#t_ICRC1">ICRC</gloss>.</p>
                <p>4. Rqst approval of planned procedure outlined above.</p>
            </div>
